2.some progromming rules
    **Analysis: Figure out what should be done and write a description of your (current) understanding of that. Such a description is called a set of re-
                quirements or a specifi cation. 
                a.Is the problem statement clear? Don't be greedy/ambitiou!!!
                b.Does the problem seem manageable, given the time, skills, and tools available? 

    **Design: Create an overall structure for the system, deciding which parts the implementation should have and how those parts should communicate.
              a. using a good library
              b.Look for parts of a solution that can be separately described and potentially used in several places in a program.

    **Implementation: Write the code, debug it, and test that it actually does what it is supposed to do.
                      a.Build a small, limited version of the program that solves a key part of the problem. 
                      b.Build a full-scale solution, ideally by using parts of the initial version.
    
    To bring out problems in our understanding, ideas, and tools. To see if details of the problem statement need changing to make the problem manageable. 
    It is rare to fi nd that we had anticipated everything when we analyzed the problem and made the initial design. We should take advantage of the 
    feedback that writing code and testing give us.
